  "prompt": "What is the best way to substitute celery seeds in a recipe?",
  "response": "If you need to substitute celery seeds in a recipe, there are several options you can consider based on the desired flavor profile:\n\n1. **Celery Salt**: This is a common substitute; however, it will add saltiness to your dish, so you'll need to adjust the amount of salt you use in the recipe. Use about one tablespoon of celery salt for each teaspoon of celery seeds.\n\n2. **Fresh Celery**: Chopped fresh celery can provide a similar flavor and texture. Use about one to two tablespoons of finely chopped celery to replace one teaspoon of celery seeds.\n\n3. **Caraway Seeds**: These seeds have a similar flavor profile and can be used as a one-to-one substitute. They may impart a slightly different taste but can work well in certain dishes.\n\n4. **Fennel Seeds**: These can be used as an alternative with a slightly sweet and licorice flavor. Use about half the amount (\u00bd teaspoon for every 1 teaspoon of celery seeds) as they have a stronger flavor.\n\n5. **Dill Seeds**: These can also serve as a substitute and have a somewhat similar flavor. Use the same amount, but keep in mind that the taste will be different.\n\n6. **Mustard Seeds**: These can work in some savory applications as a substitute, particularly in pickling or marinades, though the flavor will shift.\n\nChoose the substitute that best fits the dish you're preparing and consider the overall flavor balance.",
